# Frontend Standards

This project is built with:

- Next.js 16 App Router
- React 19
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS v4

Always follow modern Next.js best practices.

---

# Architecture

Respect the project architecture documented in:

- AGENTS.md
- docs/03-technical-architecture.md

Do not invent a different project structure.

Feature-specific code belongs inside `/features`.

Only reusable UI belongs inside `/components`.

---

# Server Components First

Default to Server Components.

Only add:

```tsx
"use client";
```

when the component requires:

- React hooks
- Browser APIs
- Event handlers
- Client-side state
- Animations that require JavaScript

Never add `"use client"` unnecessarily.

---

# Component Design

Components should:

- Have a single responsibility.
- Be small and composable.
- Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Avoid deeply nested JSX.

When a component becomes difficult to understand, split it into smaller components.

---

# Data Fetching

Prefer:

- Server Components
- Async server functions

Avoid unnecessary client-side fetching.

---

# Routing

Use the Next.js App Router.

Organize routes using route groups when appropriate.

Avoid unnecessary nested layouts.

---

# Forms

When forms are introduced:

- Use React Hook Form.
- Use Zod for validation.
- Display clear validation messages.
- Validate on both client and server when applicable.

---

# State Management

Prefer this order:

1. Server Components
2. Local React state
3. URL state
4. Context (only when necessary)

Do not introduce external global state libraries unless approved.

---

# Styling

Use:

- Tailwind CSS utilities
- Design tokens
- Shared UI components

Avoid:

- Inline styles
- Custom CSS unless necessary
- Duplicate utility combinations across components

---

# Images

Use the Next.js Image component whenever possible.

Provide meaningful alt text.

Optimize image sizes.

Lazy-load non-critical images.

---

# Performance

Prefer:

- Static rendering
- Server rendering
- Lazy loading
- Dynamic imports when beneficial

Avoid unnecessary JavaScript.

---

# Error Handling

Handle errors gracefully.

Display user-friendly messages.

Never expose internal errors to users.

---

# Code Generation Principles

Before creating a new component:

- Search for an existing reusable component.
- Reuse before creating.
- Extend before duplicating.

Avoid duplicate implementations.

---

# Definition of Done

Frontend work is complete when:

- It follows the documented architecture.
- It is responsive.
- It is type-safe.
- It is accessible.
- It is production-ready.